{"id":"2202.03108","submitter":"Jos\\'e Amig\\'o","authors":"Jos\\'e M. Amig\\'o, Karsten Keller and Valentina Unakafova","title":"On entropy, entropy-like quantities, and applications","comments":"35 pages, no figures. This is a corrected version of a paper\n  published in 2015","journal-ref":"Discrete and Continuous Dynamical Systems B 20 (2015) 3301-3344","doi":"10.3934/dcdsb.2015.20.3301","report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS math-ph math.MP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  This is a review on entropy in various fields of mathematics and science. Its\nscope is to convey a unified vision of the classical as well as some newer\nentropy notions to a broad audience with an intermediate background in\ndynamical systems and ergodic theory. Due to the breadth and depth of the\nsubject, we have opted for a compact exposition whose contents are a compromise\nbetween conceptual import and instrumental relevance. The intended technical\nlevel and the space limitation born furthermore upon the final selection of the\ntopics, which cover the three items named in the title. Specifically, the first\npart is devoted to the avatars of entropy in the traditional contexts: many\nparticle physics, information theory, and dynamical systems. This chronological\norder helps to present the materials in a didactic manner. The axiomatic\napproach will be also considered at this stage to show that, quite remarkably,\nthe essence of entropy can be encapsulated in a few basic properties. Inspired\nby the classical entropies, further akin quantities have been proposed in the\ncourse of time, mostly aimed at specific needs. A common denominator of those\naddressed in the second part of this review is their major impact on research.\nThe final part shows that, along with its profound role in the theory, entropy\nhas interesting practical applications beyond information theory and\ncommunications technology. For this sake we preferred examples from applied\nmathematics, although there are certainly nice applications in, say, physics,\ncomputer science and even social sciences. This review concludes with a\nrepresentative list of references.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Feb 2022 12:39:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-08"}
